In article <1992Oct04.084900.19815@spillman.uucp>, tye@spillman.uucp (E. Tye McQueen) writes:
>lewis@aera8700.mitre.org (Keith Lewis) writes:
>)PGP is essentially RSA performed on a bitmask which is used repeatedly on
>)a single message.
>
>Doesn't reusing the (encrypted) bit mask make long messages fairly
>easy to crack if you have ideas as to the content of the plain text?
>I guess the message would best be several times the length of the
>bit mask for this to work.

I retracted this statement after being corrected via email.  It seems that
the scheme is a little more complicated than that.  It uses the IDEA cipher
and encrypts *that* key using RSA.  

It might still be weak on very, very long messages, but nowhere near as weak
as a simple bitmask.

